## Socioeconomic and Ethical Considerations

### Digital Divide and Marginalized Populations

Approximately 60% of the global population lacks internet access, with significant disparities based on geography, gender, and socioeconomic status ([Digital Trends, 2016](https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/un-says-internet-access-is-a-human-right/)). The lack of access exacerbates existing inequalities in health, education, employment, and political participation.

### Internet Access and the Right to Development

The internet is instrumental in economic development, providing access to financial services, education, and markets. The UN Special Rapporteur highlighted that marginalized groups remain trapped in disadvantaged situations without internet access ([United Nations Human Rights Council, 2011](https://undocs.org/A/HRC/17/27)).

### Ethical Concerns of Digital Inclusion

Researchers caution that digital inclusion must consider environmental and social justice issues, such as the exploitation in mineral mining for electronics and e-waste disposal in low-income countries ([Mormina & Lucivero, 2020](https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/oureconomy/ethical-and-social-justice-agenda-for-digital-inclusion/)).

